AllLife Bank Customer Segmentation¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved. Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as upsell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the bank poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customer queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objectives

  • Analyze the customers, their spending patterns and past interaction with the bank
  • Employ clustering algorithms
  • Identify different segments in the existing customer base
  • Optimize the model using appropriate techniques
  • Provide recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers.

Data Description¶

The data provided is of various customers of a bank and their financial attributes like credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customers have contacted the bank for any queries (including visiting the bank, online and through a call center).

  • Sl_No: Primary key of the records
  • Customer Key: Customer identification number
  • Average Credit Limit: Average credit limit of each customer for all credit cards
  • Total credit cards: Total number of credit cards possessed by the customer
  • Total visits bank: Total number of visits that customer made (yearly) personally to the bank
  • Total visits online: Total number of visits or online logins made by the customer (yearly)
  • Total calls made: Total number of calls made by the customer to the bank or its customer service department (yearly)

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

Outlier treatment¶

In [29]:
# Based on the boxplots earlier, a few attributes could do with some outlier fixes. We will cap any high outlier value to Q3+(1.5*IQR

cols = ['Total_Credit_Cards', 'Total_visits_bank']
for col in cols:
    Q1 = df2[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df2[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1    
    df2[col] = np.where(df2[col] > (Q3+(1.5*IQR)),(Q3+(1.5*IQR)),df2[col])

K-means clustering¶

In [37]:
#Finding optimal no. of clusters

clusters=range(1,15)
meanDistortions=[]

for k in clusters:
    model=KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1)
    model.fit(scaled_df_z)
    prediction=model.predict(scaled_df_z)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(scaled_df_z, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / scaled_df_z.shape[0])


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
Out[37]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
  • Based on the elbow method, k=3 seems the best value for the number of clusters.
In [38]:
sil_score = []
cluster_list = list(range(2, 15))
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, random_state=1)
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((scaled_df_z))
    # centers = clusterer.cluster_centers_
    score = silhouette_score(scaled_df_z, preds)
    sil_score.append(score)

Observations¶

  • One customer segment has high credit limit, number of cards, online visits BUT low bank visits and calls. This is likely to be wealthy educated segment that is comfortable with online interactions and does not have time for visits to the branch.
  • Another customer segment has intermediate credit limit, number of cards and bank visits AND low online and phone interactions. In other industries, there is often a customer segment consisting of older customers that prefer in-person interactions. We don't have the demographic data to draw that conclusion data but this could be checked.
  • The third cluster has low credit limit, number of cards, bank visits, BUT high online and phone interactions. This could be the younger millenial and gen-Z customers that have lower income and don't prefer visiting the bank for in-person interactions.
  • Having done customer profiling with k-means clustering results, let's move on to hierarchical clustering.

# list of distance metrics
distance_metrics = ["euclidean", "chebyshev", "mahalanobis", "cityblock"]

# The Mahalanobis distance is a measure of the distance between a point P and a distribution D.
# It is a multi-dimensional generalization of the idea of measuring how many standard deviations away P is from the mean of D.

# Cityblock distance is the L1 distance, or Manhattan distance.
# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "weighted","ward","centroid"]

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    print(" ")
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        if(lm == "ward" or lm == "centroid"):
            dm="euclidean"
        Z = linkage(df3, metric=dm, method=lm) # Perform hierarchical/agglomerative clustering.
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(df3)) # Calculate the cophenetic distances between each observation 
        # in the hierarchical clustering defined by the linkage Z.

        # Returns: The cophentic correlation distance and
        # The cophenetic distance matrix in condensed form.
        print(
            "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                dm.capitalize(), lm, c
            )
        )
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = dm
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm

# list of linkage methods
linkage_methods = ["single", "complete", "average", "centroid", "ward", "weighted"]

# lists to save results of cophenetic correlation calculation
compare_cols = ["Linkage", "Cophenetic Coefficient"]

# to create a subplot image
fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(30, 60))

# We will enumerate through the list of linkage methods above
# For each linkage method, we will plot the dendrogram and calculate the cophenetic correlation
for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(df3, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(df3))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

Observations

  • The cophenetic correlation is highest for average.
  • We will move ahead with average linkage.
  • 6 appears to be the appropriate number of clusters from the dendrogram for average linkage. This process is subjective and usually needs some domain experience as well.

  • For example, based on Total_visits_bank/Total_visits_online/Total_calls_made median values, clusters 0, 1 and 2-5 are the clusters.

  • This is consistent with the earlier K-means method of clustering.

Observations¶

  • One customer segment has high credit limit, number of cards, online visits BUT low bank visits and calls. This is likely to be wealthy educated segment that is comfortable with online interactions and does not have time for visits to the branch.
  • Another customer segment has intermediate credit limit, number of cards, bank visits AND low online and phone interactions. This could be the older customers who prefer in-person interactions..
  • The third has low credit limit, number of cards, bank visits, and low online and phone interactions. This could be the unengaged customers who, if profitable, need to be engaged more.

K-means vs Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • k-means suggested three clusters whereas hierarchical clustering suggested six.
  • However, three of those six were very small and can practically be ignored as outliers.
  • So for all practical purposes, both methods have suggested three clusters.
  • Two of the those three are same in k-means vs hirarchical (not same among themselves).
  • Time it takes to do Hierarchical Clustering is much more than what it takes to do k-means clustering
  • Both can be interpreted easily, although Hierarchical clustering is easier to visualize if there are not too many data points. K-means is easier to visualize for humans if there are 1 or 2 variables.

Conclusion¶

  • EDA was performed and observations were made based on univariate and multivariate analysis.
  • Outliers were handled. There were no missing values to be taken care of, but duplicates were handled.
  • Feature engineering was done to reduce skew and outliers.
  • The attributes were found to be multi modal in nature. Hence, clustering could be expected to tease out the different customer segments.
  • K-means clustering was done and model performance was studied systematically w.r.t the number of clusters,
  • This was followed by hierarchical clustering and dendograms were studied. The model results were investigated and compared with the k-means results.
  • Individual clusters were studied and characterized to glean business insights.

Business Insights and Recommendations¶

These are the three clusters or segments of customers identified.

  • Cluster 0
    • High credit limit
    • High number of cards
    • High online visits
    • Low bank visits
    • Low calls.

      This is likely to be wealthy educated segment that is comfortable with online interactions and does not have time for visits to the branch.


  • Cluster 1

    • Intermediate level credit limit
    • Intermediate number of cards
    • Intermediate number of bank visits
    • Low count of online interactions
    • Low phone interactions

      This could be the older customers who prefer in-person interactions.


  • Cluster 2

    • Low credit limit
    • Low number of cards
    • Low number of bank visits
    • High number of online interactions
    • High number of phone interactions

      This could be the younger millennial and Gen-Z customers that have lower income and don't prefer visiting the bank or in-person interactions.


  • When it comes to customer interactions, there are clearly different groups, those who visit the bank vs. those call or interact online.

  • Cost per interaction is higher when the customer visits the bank in-person, than that of a call, which in turn, is higher than online. Hence, most of the interactions should be nudged and incentivized to be online or over a call, rather than in-person.

  • A customer segment containing about half of the customers do most of the bank visits. Most of such customers should be encouraged to online or telephonic interactions. This would save operational cost for the bank.

  • However, there are high networth customers who have very high credit limits. These customers are usually profitable for the bank and they have unique needs. Such customers are fewer in number. Such customers can be incentivized towards bank visits so that the bank can understand their needs and upsell and cross sell better. For instance, such customers can be offered a concierge service for their financial needs.

  • Two third of the calls seem to be made by a cluster of customers which is one third of the total customers. If a significant slice of this segment can be nudged to online transactions instead of calls, the bank would save money. Furthermore, using cookies and tracking, upsell and cross selling could be made more relevant for such customers.

  • If adoption of online support is difficult for certain demographicss, the bank should invest in making the web site and app easier to use. Perhaps larger fonts and decluttered look will be more amenable to being adopted by the customer segment that is not so tech savvy.
